THOUSANDS of people protested across the US on Wednesday over Republican Donald Trump&rsquo;s surprise victory in the US presidential election. On Wednesday evening, thousands of protesters thronged streets in midtown Manhattan while at a park further downtown hundreds who had gathered screamed: &ldquo;Not my president.&rdquo;In Chicago, about 1 000 people attempted to gather outside the Trump International Hotel and Tower downtown while chanting phrases like &ldquo;No Trump! No KKK! No racist USA&rdquo;. Chicago police closed roads in the area, blocking the demonstrators&rsquo; path.&ldquo;I&rsquo;m really terrified about what is happening in this country,&rdquo; said 22-year-old Adriana Rizzo, who was holding a sign that read: &ldquo;Enjoy your rights while you can.&rdquo;Protesters railed against Trump&rsquo;s marquee campaign pledge to build a wall along the border with Mexico to keep out undocumented immigrants, and other policies perceived as affecting people of colour.In his victory speech, Trump said he would be president for all Americans, saying: &ldquo;It is time for us to come together as one united people.&rdquo; &ndash; REUTERS